1215–Afdød","1215":"1215","1299":"1299","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","1230":"1230","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Timperley, Cheshire, England":"Timperley, Cheshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1215–":"1215–Overleden","1200–Male":"1200–Overleden","1210–1230":"1210–1230","1230–1299":"1230–1299","1215–Female":"1215–Overleden","1215":"1215","1299":"1299","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","1230":"1230","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Timperley, Cheshire, England":"Timperley, Cheshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1215–":"1215–Deceased","1200–Male":"1200–Deceased","1210–1230":"1210–1230","1230–1299":"1230–1299","1215–Female":"1215–Deceased","1215":"1215","1299":"1299","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","1230":"1230","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Timperley, Cheshire, England":"Timperley, Cheshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Black","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: chiefly from Middle English <i>blak(e)</i> ‘black’ (Old English <i>blæc</i>, <i>blaca</i>), a nickname given from the earliest times to a swarthy or dark-haired man. However, Middle English <i>blac</i> also meant ‘pale, wan’, a reflex of Old English <i>blāc</i> ‘pale, white’ with a shortened vowel. Compare   Blatch   and   Blick  . With rare exceptions it is impossible to disambiguate these antithetical senses in Middle English surnames. The same difficulty arises with   Blake   and   Block  .","Scottish: in Gaelic-speaking areas this name was adopted as a translation of the epithet <i>dubh</i> ‘dark, black-(haired)’, or of various other names based on Gaelic <i>dubh</i> ‘black’, see   Duff  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames directly or indirectly derived from the adjective meaning ‘black, dark’, for example German and Jewish   Schwarz   and Slavic surnames beginning with <i>Čern-</i>, <i>Chern-</i> (see   Chern   and   Cherne  ), <i>Chorn-</i>, <i>Crn-</i> or <i>Czern-</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Blagg","meanings":["English: variant of   Black   with voicing of the final consonant."]},{"name":"Blake","meanings":["English and Scottish (England and central Scotland): variant of   Black   1, meaning ‘swarthy’ or ‘dark-haired’, from a byform of the Old English adjective <i>blæc</i>, <i>blac</i> ‘black’, with change of vowel length.","English: nickname from Middle English <i>blak(e)</i> (Old English <i>blāc</i>) ‘wan, pale, white, fair’. In Middle English the two words <i>blac</i> and <i>blāc</i>, with opposite meanings, fell together as Middle English <i>blake</i>. In the absence of independent evidence as to whether the person referred to was dark or fair, it is now impossible to tell which sense was originally meant.","English (Norfolk): nickname from Middle English <i>bleik</i>, <i>blaik</i>&gt;, <i>blek(e)</i> (Old Norse <i>bleikr</i>) ‘pale or sallow’ (in complexion)."]},{"name":"Blackie","meanings":["Scottish: diminutive of   Black  .","English: nickname for a person with dark eyes, from Middle English <i>blak</i> ‘black’ + <i>eie</i> ‘eye’ (Old English <i>blæc</i> + <i>ēage</i>)."]},{"name":"Blackson","meanings":["English: patronymic from the nickname or surname   Black   + <i>-son</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Block","meanings":["German and Dutch: from Middle High German <i>bloch</i>, Middle Dutch <i>bloc</i> ‘block (of wood)’ in any of several senses, for example a topographic sense denoting a fenced field, a nickname for a large, lumpish man, or a metonymic occupational name for a shoemaker or a milliner.","English (mainly Suffolk): descriptive nickname from Middle English <i>blok</i>, <i>bloke</i>, usually meaning either ‘pale, wan, pallid’ (Old English <i>blāc</i>), but perhaps sometimes ‘black’ (of hair or appearance). The name could be interchangeable with the equally ambiguous   Black   and   Blake  . Alternatively, it may be an nickname derived from Middle English <i>blok(ke)</i>, <i>bloke</i> ‘block (of wood)’, perhaps for someone thought to be stupid or someone who made or used wooden blocks. Compare   Blocker   and 1 above.","Americanized form of Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Bloch  ."]},{"name":"Blacklock","meanings":["English (northern): nickname for someone with dark hair, from Middle English <i>blāk</i> + <i>lok(e)</i> (Old English <i>blæc</i> + <i>locc</i>), although <i>blāk</i> might mean either ‘dark’ or ‘fair’ (see   Black  ). The meaning ‘dark hair’ is the most probable since this name contrasts with   Whitlock  ."]},{"name":"Blatch","meanings":["English (Essex, but historically also in south and southwest England): nickname from Middle English <i>blache</i>, <i>bleche</i> ‘pale, pallid, of fair complexion’ (Old English <i>blǣce</i>)."]},{"name":"Blackett","meanings":["English:","nickname for a person with dark or fair hair, from Middle English <i>blak</i> ‘black’ (Old English <i>blæc</i>) or ‘fair’ (Old English <i>blāc</i>) + <i>hed</i>, <i>heved</i> ‘head’. See also   Black  .","nickname from Middle English <i>blak</i> ‘black’ + <i>hod</i> ‘hood’."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Elizabeth Black was born in 1215, in Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with John de Timperley, Snr. She died in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1215–":"1215–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1210–1230":"1210–1230","1230–1299":"1230–1299","1215–Female":"1215–Surnud","1215":"1215","1299":"1299","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","1230":"1230","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Timperley, Cheshire, England":"Timperley, Cheshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1215–":"1215–Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1210–1230":"1210–1230","1230–1299":"1230–1299","1215–Female":"1215–Kuollut","1215":"1215","1299":"1299","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","1230":"1230","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Timperley, Cheshire, England":"Timperley, Cheshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1215–":"1215–Décédée","1200–Male":"1200–Décédé","1210–1230":"1210–1230","1230–1299":"1230–1299","1215–Female":"1215–Décédée","1215":"1215","1299":"1299","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","1230":"1230","Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Timperley, Cheshire, England":"Timperley, Cheshire, Angleterre","England, United Kingdom":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Elizabeth Black est née en 1215, à Cheshire, Ang